Chapter 2: Mathematical Preliminaries

This chapter introduces the mathematical objects and tools that form the backbone of the thesis. We define the graph‑theoretic model of the network, the state spaces for energy and information, and the dynamical systems framework. We also recall basic concepts from information theory that will be used in the thermodynamic bounds.

---

2.1 Graph‑Theoretic Model

The network is modeled as a directed graph \mathcal{G} = (\mathcal{V}, \mathcal{E}) with N = |\mathcal{V}| nodes and M = |\mathcal{E}| directed edges. The nodes represent physical entities (e.g., generators, loads, routers) that can store, generate, or consume energy and process information. The edges represent the physical channels (wired or wireless) over which energy and information can be transferred.

2.1.1 Node States

Each node i \in \mathcal{V} is endowed with two state variables:

· Energy state E_i(t) \in \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0}. This may represent stored electrical energy (e.g., battery charge level), or, in an AC power network, the voltage angle or magnitude. The exact interpretation depends on the application; for the theoretical development we treat it as a scalar that obeys a conservation law.
· Information state I_i(t) \in \mathbb{R}^m. This is a vector that encodes the node’s knowledge and control signals. Typically it includes:
  · a scalar price p_i(t) used in distributed optimization,
  · a belief distribution b_i(t) (to be formalized in Chapter 5),
  · and possibly other local control variables.

For most of the analysis, we will work with the aggregated state vector
x(t) = [E_1(t), \dots, E_N(t), I_1(t)^\top, \dots, I_N(t)^\top]^\top \in \mathbb{R}^{N + N m}.

2.1.2 Edge Flows

Each directed edge (j,i) \in \mathcal{E} can carry two types of flow:

· Energy flow J_{ji}^E(t) \in \mathbb{R}. The sign convention is positive when energy flows from j to i.
· Information flow J_{ji}^I(t) \in \mathbb{R}^m. Similarly, this vector represents the net flow of information (or control signals) from j to i.

The flows are not independent; they are constrained by the physical medium. For wireless edges we will model them via SWIPT (Chapter 3), for wired edges we use the standard DC power flow approximation.

2.1.3 Graph Matrices

For a given set of edge weights w_{ij} \ge 0 (which may depend on the state or control inputs), we define:

· Adjacency matrix W \in \mathbb{R}^{N \times N} with W_{ij} = w_{ij} if (j,i) \in \mathcal{E}, and 0 otherwise.
· Degree matrix D = \operatorname{diag}(d_i) where d_i = \sum_{j} w_{ij}.
· Laplacian matrix L = D - W.

For an undirected graph, L is symmetric positive semidefinite. In the directed case, we will assume the graph is balanced (in‑degree equals out‑degree for every node) or that the Laplacian is defined via a row‑stochastic matrix; however, the core stability results rely on the algebraic connectivity of the underlying undirected version or on the existence of a positive real part of the eigenvalues of L.

We denote the eigenvalues of L (for the symmetric case) as
0 = \lambda_1 \le \lambda_2 \le \dots \le \lambda_N. The second smallest eigenvalue \lambda_2 is called the algebraic connectivity (Fiedler value). It quantifies how well the graph is connected: \lambda_2 > 0 if and only if the graph is connected.

---

2.2 Dynamical Systems

We consider continuous‑time dynamical systems of the form

\dot{x} = f(x,t)

with x \in \mathbb{R}^n. In our context, f will be piecewise continuous in t and locally Lipschitz in x to ensure existence and uniqueness of solutions.

2.2.1 Equilibrium Points

A point x^* is an equilibrium if f(x^*,t) \equiv 0 for all t. For our coupled system, an equilibrium corresponds to a state where energy injections balance loads, information flows have reached consensus, and the coupling terms vanish.

2.2.2 Stability Notions

We will use standard stability concepts:

· Lyapunov stability: An equilibrium x^* is stable if for every \epsilon > 0 there exists \delta > 0 such that \|x(0)-x^*\| < \delta implies \|x(t)-x^*\| < \epsilon for all t \ge 0.
· Asymptotic stability: It is stable and \lim_{t\to\infty} x(t) = x^* for initial conditions sufficiently close.
· Global asymptotic stability (GAS): The equilibrium attracts all initial conditions.
· Exponential stability: There exist constants c,\alpha > 0 such that \|x(t)-x^*\| \le c e^{-\alpha t} \|x(0)-x^*\|.
· Input‑to‑state stability (ISS): For bounded disturbances d(t), the solution satisfies
    \|x(t)-x^*\| \le \beta(\|x(0)-x^*\|,t) + \gamma(\|d\|_\infty) with \beta a class‑\mathcal{KL} function and \gamma a class‑\mathcal{K} function.

Our stability theorem (Chapter 4) will establish ISS with an exponential decay rate.

2.2.3 Comparison Lemma and Grönwall’s Inequality

We will frequently use the Grönwall inequality: If \dot{V}(t) \le -\alpha V(t) + \beta(t) with \alpha > 0 and \beta(t) integrable, then
V(t) \le e^{-\alpha t} V(0) + \int_0^t e^{-\alpha (t-s)} \beta(s)\,ds.

---

2.3 Information‑Theoretic Quantities

For the thermodynamic bounds, we need measures of information. Let P and Q be probability measures on a common space \Omega.

· Kullback‑Leibler (KL) divergence:
  D_{\text{KL}}(P \| Q) = \int \log\frac{dP}{dQ}\, dP,
  defined when P is absolutely continuous with respect to Q.
· Mutual information: For random variables X,Y with joint distribution P_{XY} and product of marginals P_X \otimes P_Y,
  I(X;Y) = D_{\text{KL}}(P_{XY} \| P_X \otimes P_Y).
· Predictive information (following Bialek et al.) is the mutual information between the present state and a future observation. In our context, for node i with belief b_i and environment \mathcal{E},
  I_{\text{pred},i} = I(\text{state}_i; \text{future environment}).
· Memory information is the mutual information between the state and past environment:
  I_{\text{mem},i} = I(\text{state}_i; \text{past environment}).

These quantities will be related via the dissipation bound in Chapter 3.

