Appendix A: Derivation of the Dissipation Bound (Quenneville–Sivak)

We provide a self‑contained derivation of the thermodynamic bound used in Chapter 3. The result is originally from Quenneville and Sivak (2018) and is presented here for completeness.

Consider a system coupled to a thermal reservoir at temperature T and exchanging energy and information with its environment. Let the system’s state at time t be x_t, and let the environment’s past and future trajectories be denoted by \mathcal{P} and \mathcal{F}, respectively. The total entropy production over a time interval [0,T] is \sigma = \Delta S_{\text{sys}} + \Delta S_{\text{env}}. For a process that starts and ends in equilibrium, \Delta S_{\text{sys}} = 0, so \sigma = \Delta S_{\text{env}}. In terms of energy dissipation, W_{\text{diss}} = k_B T \sigma = k_B T \Delta S_{\text{env}}.

The mutual information between the system’s trajectory and the past environment is I_{\text{mem}} = I(x_{[0,T]}; \mathcal{P}). The mutual information with the future environment is I_{\text{pred}} = I(x_{[0,T]}; \mathcal{F}). Using the fluctuation theorem and the data‑processing inequality, Quenneville and Sivak proved:

\sigma \ge I_{\text{mem}} - I_{\text{pred}}.

Sketch of the proof. The key step is to relate the entropy production to the mutual information between the system and the environment. By considering the time‑reversed process and using the fact that the system’s state is a deterministic function of the past environment under a Markovian assumption, one obtains:

\sigma = D_{\text{KL}}(P_{\text{forward}} \| P_{\text{backward}}) \ge I(\text{state}; \mathcal{F} | \mathcal{P}) - I(\text{state}; \mathcal{P} | \mathcal{F}),

which simplifies to I_{\text{mem}} - I_{\text{pred}} after some algebra. For a detailed derivation, see Quenneville and Sivak (2018), Section III.

