Appendix C: Proof of Theorem 4.2 (Stability with Delays)

We sketch the proof using a Lyapunov‑Krasovskii functional. Consider the delayed system:

\dot{p}_i(t) = \kappa \sum_j w_{ij} \bigl(p_j(t-\tau_{ij}(t)) - p_i(t)\bigr) + \lambda E_i(t),

with delays bounded by \tau_{\max}. The energy dynamics are unchanged and delay‑free. Define the candidate functional

V(t) = \frac12 \|E(t)\|^2 + \frac12 \|p(t)\|^2 + \mu \int_{-\tau_{\max}}^0 \int_{t+\theta}^t \|\dot{p}(s)\|^2 \, ds\, d\theta,

with \mu > 0 to be chosen. Differentiating V and using the fact that \dot{p} is bounded by the dynamics, one obtains

\dot{V} \le -\alpha \|E\|^2 - \beta \|p\|^2 + \gamma \|d\|^2 + (\text{terms involving delays}).

By applying the Wirtinger inequality and bounding the delay terms, we get a condition of the form

\dot{V} \le -\delta V + \eta \|d\|^2,

provided that

\tau_{\max} < \frac{\lambda_{\min} \underline{d}}{2\kappa^2 \bar{w}^2 N^2}.

The details follow standard Lyapunov‑Krasovskii techniques (see, e.g., [Olfati‑Saber & Murray, 2004]). Once the inequality holds, the same Grönwall argument yields ISS.

