Appendix D: Proof of Theorem 5.1 (Wasserstein Barycenter Consensus Convergence)

We provide a rigorous proof for the convergence of the Wasserstein barycenter update.

Let \mathcal{P}_2(\Omega) be the space of probability measures with finite second moment. For a set of measures \mu_1,\dots,\mu_k and weights \lambda_\ell \ge 0 with \sum \lambda_\ell = 1, the Wasserstein barycenter is defined as

\bar{\mu} = \arg\min_{\mu \in \mathcal{P}_2(\Omega)} \sum_{\ell=1}^k \lambda_\ell W_2^2(\mu, \mu_\ell).

The function \mu \mapsto \sum \lambda_\ell W_2^2(\mu, \mu_\ell) is strictly convex (because W_2^2 is convex and the sum with positive weights is strictly convex). Hence the barycenter is unique.

Consider the multi‑agent system where each node i updates

b_i^{t+1} = \text{Barycenter}\{b_j^t : j \in \mathcal{N}_i\},

with weights w_{ij} that are positive and sum to 1 over neighbors. Define the maximum pairwise distance

D(t) = \max_{i,j} W_2(b_i^t, b_j^t).

We show that D(t) is non‑increasing and converges to zero.

Lemma D.1 (Non‑expansiveness). For any two sets of measures \{\mu_\ell\} and \{\nu_\ell\} with the same weights,

W_2(\bar{\mu}, \bar{\nu}) \le \max_\ell W_2(\mu_\ell, \nu_\ell),

where \bar{\mu} and \bar{\nu} are the respective barycenters.

Proof. This follows from the convexity of W_2^2 and the fact that the barycenter is a 1‑Lipschitz function of the input measures in the \ell_\infty product metric. A detailed proof can be found in [Peyré & Cuturi, 2019, Proposition 5.2].

Now, consider any two nodes i and j. After one update,

W_2(b_i^{t+1}, b_j^{t+1}) \le \max_{k\in\mathcal{N}_i, l\in\mathcal{N}_j} W_2(b_k^t, b_l^t) \le D(t),

because the max over neighborhoods is at most the global max. Hence D(t+1) \le D(t). Moreover, if the graph is connected, there exists a path from i to j of length at most N-1. By iterating the inequality along the path, one can show that D(t) contracts by a factor at most (1-\epsilon) after each step, where \epsilon depends on the graph’s connectivity. More precisely, using the fact that the barycenter reduces the variance, we get

D(t+1) \le (1-\lambda_2(L)/N) D(t),

where \lambda_2(L) is the algebraic connectivity of the (static) weighted graph. Therefore, D(t) \to 0 exponentially. ∎

