Appendix E: Proof of Theorem 5.2 (Byzantine Resilience)

We sketch the proof of the trimmed Wasserstein median consensus.

Assume the network is (2f+1)-connected. At each step, each correct node receives m beliefs from its neighbors, trims the f farthest (in W_2 distance) from the rest, and computes the barycenter of the remaining m-f beliefs. Because the graph is (2f+1)-connected, even after removing any f nodes, the remaining subgraph is still connected. This ensures that each correct node has at least 2f+1 neighbors, and after trimming, it retains at least f+1 correct neighbors (since at most f are Byzantine). Thus, the set of retained beliefs contains a majority of correct ones.

The key lemma is that the trimmed barycenter is a contraction in the sense that the distance between the trimmed barycenters of two correct nodes is at most the maximum distance between their retained correct beliefs. Since the correct beliefs converge to the true environment due to the non‑expansiveness of the barycenter, and the Byzantine beliefs are bounded away from the truth (they can be arbitrary but the majority rule eliminates them), the consensus among correct nodes is achieved. The formal proof follows the standard Byzantine consensus argument for the Euclidean case, adapted to the Wasserstein metric via the non‑expansiveness property. See [Casjens et al., 2025] for a detailed treatment.

