Appendix F: Proof of Theorem 6.1 (Convergence of Primal‑Dual Dynamics)

We provide a sketch of the proof for the convergence of the distributed primal‑dual algorithm.

Consider the Lagrangian

\mathcal{L}(P,E,p) = \sum_i (C_i(P_i) + D_i(E_i)) + p^\top \left( \sum_i P_i - L_{\text{total}} \right) + \frac{\kappa}{2} \sum_{i,j} w_{ij} (p_i - p_j)^2,

where the last term is a regularizer that enforces consensus (it can be interpreted as the Laplacian term in the price dynamics). The primal‑dual dynamics are:

\dot{P}_i = -\nabla_{P_i} \mathcal{L}, \quad \dot{E}_i = -\nabla_{E_i} \mathcal{L}, \quad \dot{p}_i = \nabla_{p_i} \mathcal{L}.

Because the Lagrangian is convex in (P,E) and concave in p (the regularizer is convex in p), the dynamics are a saddle‑point flow. By standard results (e.g., [Boyd et al., 2011]), the trajectories converge to the unique saddle point, which corresponds to the optimum of the original problem. The convergence rate is exponential if the Lagrangian is strongly convex–strongly concave; the regularizer provides the necessary strong concavity in p (since the graph Laplacian has a positive eigenvalue gap). The proof uses the Lyapunov function

V = \frac12 \|P-P^*\|^2 + \frac12 \|E-E^*\|^2 + \frac12 \|p-p^*\|^2,

and shows that \dot{V} \le -\alpha V near the optimum, using the fact that the gradient of the Lagrangian is Lipschitz. ∎

