Appendix G: Proof of Theorem 6.2 (Fundamental Efficiency Bound)

We give a rigorous derivation of the bound.

From Quenneville–Sivak, we have for each node i:

\beta \dot{W}_{\text{diss},i} \ge \frac{d}{dt}(I_{\text{mem},i} - I_{\text{pred},i}).

Now, we relate I_{\text{mem},i} - I_{\text{pred},i} to the KL divergence between the belief b_i and the stationary distribution \pi_i^{\text{ss}} of the environment. By the chain rule for mutual information,

I_{\text{mem},i} - I_{\text{pred},i} = I(\text{state}_i; \text{past}) - I(\text{state}_i; \text{future}).

Using the fact that the environment is stationary and ergodic, one can show that

I(\text{state}_i; \text{future}) = I(\text{state}_i; \text{past}) - D_{\text{KL}}(b_i \| \pi_i^{\text{ss}}) + \text{const},

where the constant depends on the mutual information between the past and future given the state. This is derived from the Markov property and the fact that the optimal predictor is the stationary distribution. A detailed derivation is given in [Karbowski, 2024]. Substituting, we get

I_{\text{mem},i} - I_{\text{pred},i} \ge D_{\text{KL}}(b_i \| \pi_i^{\text{ss}}) + \text{const}.

The constant can be absorbed by redefining the initial condition. Integrating over time,

\beta \int_0^T \dot{W}_{\text{diss},i} \, dt \ge \int_0^T \frac{d}{dt} D_{\text{KL}}(b_i(t) \| \pi_i^{\text{ss}}) \, dt = D_{\text{KL}}(b_i(T) \| \pi_i^{\text{ss}}) - D_{\text{KL}}(b_i(0) \| \pi_i^{\text{ss}}).

Summing over i gives the theorem. ∎

