Appendix H: Spectral Properties of the Power‑Aware Laplacian

We collect some useful bounds on the eigenvalues of L(\sigma). Let w_{\min} = \min_{i,j} w_{ij} (over active edges) and let L_0 be the Laplacian of the underlying unweighted graph with edges where w_{ij}>0. Then

\lambda_2(L(\sigma)) \ge w_{\min} \lambda_2(L_0).

This follows from the Rayleigh quotient: for any v \perp \mathbf{1},

v^\top L(\sigma) v = \sum_{i<j} w_{ij} (v_i - v_j)^2 \ge w_{\min} \sum_{i<j} (v_i - v_j)^2 = w_{\min} v^\top L_0 v.

Hence \lambda_2(L(\sigma)) \ge w_{\min} \lambda_2(L_0).

Similarly, if the graph is complete and all weights are equal to w, then \lambda_2(L) = N w. Thus, the connectivity can be increased by raising the weights, i.e., by allocating more power to information transmission.

