Appendix I: Numerical Methods for Wasserstein Barycenter

For computational implementation, we use the Sinkhorn algorithm with entropic regularization. Given measures \mu_1,\dots,\mu_k on a discrete grid of M points, the entropic barycenter is

\min_{\mu} \sum_{\ell=1}^k \lambda_\ell W_{2,\varepsilon}^2(\mu, \mu_\ell),

where W_{2,\varepsilon}^2(\mu,\nu) = \min_{\pi} \langle C, \pi \rangle + \varepsilon \sum_{i,j} \pi_{ij} \log \pi_{ij} with C_{ij} = \|x_i - y_j\|^2. This problem is convex and can be solved by alternating between projecting onto the marginal constraints (the Sinkhorn iterations). The algorithm converges linearly in the number of iterations. For details, see [Peyré & Cuturi, 2019].

